[This week's report is very sobering. Rather than report on possible interruption of transmission of polioviruses, there have been 5 WPV associated cases and 20 cVDPV associated cases reported during this past week. As of the date of these data (27 Nov 2019) there have now been a total of 112 WPV1 associated cases with dates of onset during 2019. Even more sobering is that as of 27 Nov 2019, there have now been 177 cVDPV associated cases. For the past several years, the number of cVDPV associated paralytic cases has surpassed the number of WPV associated cases. During 2018, there were 33 cases associated with WPV infection compared with 104 cases associated with cVDPV infection. During 2017 there were 22 cases associated with WPV infection compared with 96 cases associated with cVDPV infection. It's not easy for a country to continue to successfully promote vaccination when cases are associated with infection with a VDPV. Are we approaching the time when OPV (live attenuated oral poliovirus vaccine) should be eliminated and only the IPV (inactivated poliovirus vaccine) should be used?

Case reports during the past week have involved 6 countries. Only Pakistan reported WPV associated cases (5 WPV1)) whereas 6 countries reported cVDPV associated cases: Pakistan (2 cVDPV2), DR Congo (5 cVDPV2), Benin (4 cVDPV2), Ghana (4 cVDPV2), Philippines (3 cVDPV2) and Togo (2 cVDPV2).

For a map showing the locations of both WPV-associated cases and cVDPV-associated cases, see http://polioeradication.org/polio-today/polio-now/.

As done in previous posts, to visualize all of this activity, I am putting links to HealthMap/ProMED-mail maps of countries with poliovirus activity during 2018 and 2019 below. The size of the list remains impressive, now with 23 countries: 16 in Africa, 5 in Asia, and 3 in the Western Pacific, with either WPV or cVDPV isolates in their countries (and in the case of Pakistan, both WPV1 and cVDPV2). An important reminder is that positive environmental samples means that the virus is circulating in the area where the samples have been obtained. Hence, if a susceptible individual is infected with the virus, there is a chance the person may develop paralytic disease.

